  "prompt": "How does the law define illegal money laundering activities?",
  "response": "Money laundering is generally defined by law as the process of making illegally-obtained money appear legal by passing it through complex financial transactions. Specific legal definitions can vary by jurisdiction, but typically involve three key stages:\n\n1. Placement: Introducing illegal funds into the financial system\n2. Layering: Concealing the source through complex transactions\n3. Integration: Reintroducing the money into the economy as seemingly legitimate funds\n\nSpecific activities often considered illegal include:\n- Structuring financial transactions to avoid reporting requirements\n- Transferring funds through multiple accounts\n- Using shell companies to hide money's origin\n- Mixing illegal funds with legitimate business revenue\n\nLaws like the Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering regulations in the US provide detailed legal frameworks for identifying and prosecuting such activities.",
